@Node "Introduction" "ClipHistory.guide/Introduction"

	@{u}@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

This is a program that I thought about writing for a long time (a year or
so! :) before I actually implemented it. I first got the idea when I had
used the history feature of @{b}PowerSnap@{ub} (by Nico François) a little while. I
soon realised that it was a very convenient feature.

The problem is that other programs uses the clipboard as well. The history
@{b}PowerSnap@{ub} maintains only applies to the text that @{b}PowerSnap@{ub} writes to the
clipboard, not the ones e.g. my text editor writes. And I thought that it
would indeed be useful to have them in a history too.

One problem with such a history is that it easily can eat up a lot of
memory, since cuts and copies in an editor can be rather large at times. To
remedy this problem, there are several filtering options, that limits the
amount of memory @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} may use. But more about this later on in this
document.

One interesting detail: @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} is a completely system friendly
program, in that it doesn't patch any functions at all (unless you really
want it to! :). It only uses well documented features of the operating
system. This does have a minor drawback: @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} can miss clips, if
several clips are written in a very short time. But this shouldn't be any
problem, I think.. :)

@EndNode


