@Node "System requirements" "ClipHistory.guide/System requirements"

	@{u}@{b}System requirements@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} have very modest system requirements. It needs OS 2.04 or
better, although OS 3.0 or better will make @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} operate slightly
better.

If you have @{b}ReqTools@{ub} (by Nico François and yours truly ;) installed, then
@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will use @{b}ReqTools@{ub} for its requesters (you can disable this if
you like). Otherwise the "normal" system requesters will be used.

@EndNode


@Node "Installation" "ClipHistory.guide/Installation"

	@{u}@{b}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} is easy to install. Simply copy the program (and its icon) to
@{b}WBStartup@{ub}, or whereever you find convenient. If you have OS 2.1 or higher,
you might want to copy a catalog file as well, to make @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} operate
in another language than english.

The easiest way is to let the @{b}Installer@{ub} do it. If not, copy the file
@{b}cliphistory.catalog@{ub}, found in the @{b}Catalogs/<language>@{ub} drawer, to
@{b}Locale:Catalogs/<language>@{ub} (or to the drawer @{b}Catalogs/<language>@{ub} in the
same drawer as you placed @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}). In either case, <language> should
be one of the languages you have selected in the @{b}Locale@{ub} preferences
editor.

If there is no catalog file for your language, please try to fill in the
file @{b}Empty.ct@{ub} in the @{b}Catalogs@{ub} drawer and send it to me. I will
then include the catalog in the next release of @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}. It would be
nice if you could translate the @{b}Installer@{ub} script as well.

@EndNode


@Node "Usage" "ClipHistory.guide/Usage"

	@{u}@{b}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

To use @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}, you first make sure that the tooltypes are set up
properly. Then start it. You can also start if from a shell, but then you
must remember to @{b}Run@{ub} it (and to write suitable arguments). To make it
permanently installed, simply drop it into @{b}WBStartup@{ub}, or enter a suitable
line in your @{b}S:User-Startup@{ub} file.

@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} installs itself as a commodity, so you can use the Commodities
@{b}Exchange@{ub} program to show the interface, disable/enable it, or remove it
completely. Starting @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} a second time (for the same clipboard
unit (option @{b}CLIPUNIT@{ub})) will cause the first copy to show the interface.
Pressing the hotkey will also open the interface (option @{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}). See
@{"Options" Link "Options"} for more information.

The user interface of @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} is very simple; it contains of a window
with a list gadget. This list contains all the remembered clips. There is
also a menu strip attached (see @{"Menus" Link "Menus"}).

The text showed in the list is either the text - if it is a text clip - or
the type of the IFF clip (everything on the clipboard should be in IFF
format), followed by its size (in bytes). If you have OS 3.0 or higher, the
non-text clips will be shown in bold.

To select an item in the list, you either click once on it with the mouse,
or you use the cursur Up/Down keys (optionally with the Shift/Alt/Ctrl
qualifiers) to highlight the requested item.

To copy an item to the clipboard, you double-click on the item, or press
Return when the proper item is selected. Unless the @{b}STICKY@{ub} option (see
@{"Options" Link "Options"}) have been used, the window will close.

To display a clip, you can enter Alt-Return

Esc closes the window.

@EndNode


@Node "Menus" "ClipHistory.guide/Menus"

	@{u}@{b}Menus@{ub}@{uu}

The window @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} opens have the following menus:

@{b}Project@{ub}
	@{b}About...@{ub}
		Show some information about the program and the history.

	@{b}Hide@{ub}
		Close the window, but don't quit.

	@{b}Quit@{ub}
		Close the window and quit.

@{b}Edit@{ub}
	@{b}Open clipboard...@{ub}
		This will open a file requester, allowing you to select a
		file that will be written to the clipboard. If it is an IFF
		file, it will be copied as it is, otherwise it will be
		written as an IFF FTXT file.

	@{b}Save clipboard as...@{ub}
		This will open a file requester, allowing you to select a
		filename to which the current clipboard contents will be
		written.

	@{b}Show clipboard...@{ub}
		This will write the current clipboard contents to a
		temprary file, and start the @{b}SHOWCLIP@{ub} program to show this
		file (see @{"Options" Link "Options"} for more information),

	@{b}Clear clipboard@{ub}
		Simply clear the clipboard, by writing a special (and
		small) IFF EMTY file to it.

@{b}History@{ub}
	@{b}Delete item...@{ub}
		This will delete the currently selected item. You can also
		press Del to do this.

	@{b}Delete all items...@{ub}
		This will delete @{i}all @{ui}clips in the list. You can also press
		Shift-Del to do this.

	@{b}Save item as...@{ub}
		This allows you to save the currently selected item to a
		file of your choice.

	@{b}Show item...@{ub}
		This will write the currently selected item to a temporary
		file, and start the @{b}SHOWCLIP@{ub} program to show this file
		(see @{"Options" Link "Options"} for more information),

@{b}Options@{ub}
	@{b}Create icons?@{ub}
		If checked, then icons will be created for the files you
		save. This is the same as the option @{b}CREATEICONS@{ub} (see
		@{"Options" Link "Options"}).

	@{b}Save text as IFF?@{ub}
		If checked, then text clips (those that shows up as
		"normal" text in the window) will be saved as IFF files. If
		you save them as normal text, then some information might
		be lost (technical note: all CHRS chunks will be saved, but
		no other(s)). Same as the option @{b}TEXTASIFF@{ub} (see @{"Options" Link "Options"}).

	@{b}ReqTools?@{ub}
		If checked, then @{b}ReqTools@{ub} will be used for requesters, if
		it's available. Same as the option @{b}REQTOOLS@{ub} (see @{"Options" Link "Options"}).

	@{b}Sticky?@{ub}
		If checked, then then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} won't close the window
		after writing a clip to the clipboard. Same as the option
		@{b}STICKY@{ub} (see @{"Options" Link "Options"}).

@EndNode


@Node "Options" "ClipHistory.guide/Options"

	@{u}@{b}Options@{uu}@{ub}

Options can be specified in the tooltypes (when starting from the
@{b}Workbench@{ub}) or on the command line (when starting from a @{b}Shell@{ub}).

@{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub}
	This value specifies the priority @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will have in the
	commodities input chain. This priority only applies to the hotkey.
	Default is 0. Accepted range is -128 to 127.

@{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}
	This string specifies the hotkey that will open the window. Default
	is "control lalt c". Please refer to your Amiga manual for more
	information about hotkey descriptors.

@{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will open the
	window upon startup (this is the default). Use NO to disable this.

@{b}CLIPUNIT@{ub}
	This value specifies the clipboard unit to use. Default is 0.
	Accepted range is 0 to 255.

	You can start one copy of @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} for each clipboard unit. In
	Commodities @{b}Exchange@{ub}, the name will be "ClipHistory <unit>", where
	<unit> is the number you specify here.

	@{i}Note: @{ui} @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} can be made resident. This is useful if you
	start several copies of @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}, so that all copies share the
	same code (which saves quite a bit of memory).

@{b}TOOLPRI@{ub}
	This value specifies the "normal" priority for @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}. To
	make sure that @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} doesn't miss any clips, even if the
	computer is doing much work, you might want to rise the task
	priority of @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}. Default is to use whatever priority
	@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} was started in (this is normally 0). Accepted
	range is -128 to 4.

	@{i}Note: @{ui}The @{b}Workbench@{ub} also supports the @{b}TOOLPRI@{ub} tooltype. It was
	added to @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} so that @{b}Shell@{ub} users easily can change the
	priority as well.

@{b}WORKPRI@{ub}
	Some operations @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} does can take a little time. Here you
	can specify the priority @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} should use during this time,
	so that other programs can run normally. Usually a negative value
	should be entered. The default is not to change the priority.
	Accepted range is -128 to 4.

@{b}SILENT@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} won't display any
	requesters or flash the screen for various clip operation errors,
	like when there was a problem reading/writing to the clipboard, or
	when there wasn't enough memory to save a clip. Default is NO.

@{b}PORTNAME@{ub}
	This string lets you specify the name of the @{b}ARexx@{ub} port
	@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} opens. The default is "CLIPHISTORYx", where "x" is
	the clipboard unit the history operates on (see @{b}CLIPUNIT@{ub}). If you
	enter an empty string (""), then no @{b}ARexx@{ub} port will be opened. If
	@{b}ARexx@{ub} isn't installed, then no @{b}ARexx@{ub} port will be opened either.

@{b}NEXTKEY@{ub}
	This string specifies the hotkey that will activate the next item
	in the history (if possible) and paste that one to the clipboard
	without opening the window. Useful when you have snapped a few
	strings and want to paste them somewere. This works even if the
	window should happen to be open. Default is no hotkey ("").

@{b}PREVKEY@{ub}
	This string specifies a hotkey that works much like @{b}NEXTKEY@{ub}, but
	it will paste the previous history item (if possible) instead.
	Default is no hotkey ("").

@{b}AUTOSELECT@{ub}
	By default, @{b}NEXTKEY@{ub} and @{b}PREVKEY@{ub} will fail (flashing the display to
	inform you about it) if no clip item is selected. If this option is
	set to YES, then @{b}NEXTKEY@{ub} will automatically select the first item
	in the list, and @{b}PREVKEY@{ub} will select the last item.

@{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub}
	This string specifies the public screen on which @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}
	should open its window on. Default is the frontmost screen if it is
	public (if @{b}OPENONALL@{ub} is on, it will use the frontmost screen
	anyway), or the default public screen.

@{b}OPENONALL@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will open on the
	frontmost screen, regardless if it is public or not. Default is NO.

	@{i}Note: @{ui}In order for this to work properly, a function in @{b}Intuition@{ub}
	(@{b}CloseScreen()@{ub}) needs to be patched (this patch is only installed
	if this option have been activated). If some other program have
	patched the same program and you try to exit, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}
	will exit anyway, but it will leave a small memory allocation, to
	make sure there aren't any problems. If you have a @{b}SetMan@{ub}-like
	program installed, this should never happen.

@{b}FONTNAME@{ub}
	This string specifies the name of the font (including the ".font"
	extension) to use for the window/menus. If not specified, then the
	current screen font is used. You must specify both @{b}FONTNAME@{ub} and
	@{b}FONTSIZE@{ub}.

	Hint: If you have @{b}MagicWB@{ub}, it can be a good idea to use e.g.
	XHelvetica, since that font is "complete", i.e. chars that normally
	aren't printable holds graphics to identify the char in question.

@{b}FONTSIZE@{ub}
	This value specifies the size of the above font. You must specify
	both @{b}FONTNAME@{ub} and @{b}FONTSIZE@{ub}.

@{b}WINDOWLEFT@{ub}
	This value specifies the initial left edge of the window. Default
	is to center the window on the screen.

@{b}WINDOWTOP@{ub}
	This value specifies the initial top edge of the window. Default is
	to center the window on the screen.

@{b}WINWIDTH@{ub}
	This value specifies the initial width of the window. Default is
	<width of the screen> / 2.

@{b}WINHEIGHT@{ub}
	This value specifies the initial height of the window. Default is
	<height of the screen> / 3.

@{b}CENTERMOUSE@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will center the
	window under the mouse. This option will override the options
	@{b}SAVEPOS@{ub}, @{b}WINDOWLEFT@{ub} and @{b}WINDOWTOP@{ub}, if set to YES. Default is NO.

@{b}NORMALGLYPHS@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will not use custom
	symbols in the menus (only when running under OS 3.0 or higher).
	This can be useful if you e.g. use @{b}MagicMenu@{ub}, which currently
	doesn't handle these symbols properly.

@{b}SCREENMENUFONT@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will use the
	current screen font for the menus, rather than the font specified
	in @{b}FONTNAME@{ub} and @{b}FONTSIZE@{ub}.

@{b}STICKY@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} won't close the
	window after writing a clip to the clipboard. Default is NO.

@{b}SINGLECLICK@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then a single click with the mouse on
	an item is enough to paste it to the clipboard. Click with Shift,
	Alt or Ctrl pressed to select an item without pasting (a
	doubleclick with any qualifier down will also paste).

	If set to NO, a doubleclick is needed to paste the item. A single
	click with any qualifier down will then paste the item. Default is
	NO.

@{b}POPSCREEN@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will - when closing
	its window - restore the screen that was in front before the window
	was opened. This only needs to be done if that screen wasn't
	public. Default is NO.

	@{i}Note: @{ui}Using @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub}, @{b}OPENONALL@{ub} or @{b}STICKY@{ub} will disable this
	option.

@{b}SAVEPOS@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will remember the
	current position of the window when you close it. Otherwise it will
	reopen using the position specified in the arguments (or the
	defaults). Default is NO.

@{b}SAVESIZE@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will remember the
	current size of the window when you close it. Otherwise it will
	reopen using the size specified in the arguments (or the defaults).
	Default is NO.

@{b}MAXCLIPS@{ub}
	This value specifies the maximum number of clips that the history
	can hold. Default is 32767. Accepted range is 0 to 32767. Note that
	0 really means 1.

@{b}MAXCLIPSIZE@{ub}
	If the clip is larger than this value, then it will not be saved in
	the history. Using 0 here will disable the history. Default is the
	@{b}MAXMEM@{ub} limit (see below) if that one is specified. Otherwise there
	is no limit (other than the amount of free memory).

@{b}MINCLIPSIZE@{ub}
	If the clip is smaller than this value, then it will not be saved
	in the history. The default is 0.

	Please note that this value refers to the total size of the clip,
	including the extra overhead due to the IFF file format. For a
	minimal IFF file (as saved by e.g. @{b}PowerSnap@{ub}), this overhead is 20
	bytes. Also, an IFF file is (read: should be) always padded to an
	even number of bytes. Thus, a relatively useful minimum could be
	22, which would force each saved clip to have at least 3 data bytes
	(when talking about saved text at least).

@{b}MAXMEM@{ub}
	This value specifies how much memory the history may use at most.
	The history is dynamically allocated, using so called memory pools
	(to reduce memory fragmentation). Thus, the actual amount of memory
	used might be a little more than this value. Default is no max
	(other than the amount of free memory).

@{b}MATCH@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, check all new items against the last
	one, and only save the new one if it is different. Default is NO.

@{b}FULLMATCH@{ub}
	Like @{b}MATCH@{ub}, but check @{i}all @{ui}entries instead. This option overrides
	@{b}MATCH@{ub}. Default is NO.

	@{i}Note: @{ui}This can take some time if you have a (very) large history
	(@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will use the @{b}WORKPRI@{ub} during this check). If more than
	one clip is written to the clipboard during this time, only the
	last one will be remembered.

@{b}CASE@{ub}
	If this option is set to NO, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will ignore the case
	when comparing two clips (when either @{b}MATCH@{ub} or @{b}FULLMATCH@{ub} have been
	enavled). Obviously, this is only possible when the clip contains
	text (FTXT). Default is YES.

@{b}FILTER@{ub}
	Here you can specify which IFF types that should be saved (or not
	saved, if @{b}REJECT@{ub} have been specified). Space separate the items.
	Case @{i}is @{ui}important. There are many different IFF types available,
	and I can't mention them all, but here is a list over the most
	common ones:

	@{b}FTXT@{ub}
		Text. E.g. ConClip and PowerSnap saves these ones. Text
		editors are likely to write them as well.

	@{b}ILBM@{ub}
		Graphics/palettes. Saved by e.g. IconEdit.

	@{b}8SVX@{ub}
		Sound (samples).

@{b}REJECT@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, them the @{b}FILTER@{ub} (see above) will
	reject the clip on a match instead of accept it, i.e. it reverses
	the action of the filter. Default is NO.

@{b}SHOWCLIP@{ub}
	This option lets you specify the program to use to view a clip.
	@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will write the currently selected clip (or the
	contents of the clipboard) to a temporary file, and then start this
	program with the filename as the first argument. Note that this
	file will not be deleted by @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} (you can do this with a
	script if you want to). Default is "MultiView".

@{b}TEMPDIR@{ub}
	This option specifies were @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} should write the temprary
	files that the @{b}SHOWCLIP@{ub} program should read and display. Default
	is "T:".

@{b}FILETYPE@{ub}
	If this option is specified, then the file type will be the second
	argument to the @{b}SHOWCLIP@{ub} program. This way, a simple @{b}Shell@{ub} script
	can be used to view the file (see the included @{b}ShowClip@{ub} script).
	This argument will be "text" if the clip was written as a simple
	text file (@{b}TEXTASIFF@{ub} is set to NO), otherwise the IFF file type
	will be the second argumet (see @{b}FILTER@{ub} for more information about
	IFF types). Default is NO.

@{b}SAVEPATH@{ub}
	This option lets you specify the directory in which the "Save
	clipboard..."/"Save item..." file requester should open the first
	time (it remembers the last used directory). The default is to open
	in the current directory for @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}

@{b}TEXTASIFF@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES then FTXT clips will be saved as an
	IFF file, rather than a normal ASCII-file. All clips that shows up
	as "normal" text in the window are FTXT clips. Note that some
	information may be lost if a clip is saved as ASCII (e.g. font
	information). Default is NO.

@{b}CREATEICONS@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then an icon will be created for each
	clip that is saved. Default is NO.

@{b}REQTOOLS@{ub}
	If this option is set to YES, then @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will use @{b}ReqTools@{ub}
	for requesters, if it should be available. Default is YES.


@EndNode


@Node "ARexx" "ClipHistory.guide/ARexx"

	@{u}@{b}ARexx@{uu}@{ub}

As of version 2.0, @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} have an @{b}ARexx@{ub} port. This means you can
access the history and the clipboard from your @{b}ARexx@{ub} programs. The port is
called "CLIPHISTORYx" by default (where x is the clipboard unit, specified
with the @{b}CLIPUNIT@{ub} argument), but you may change this by using the @{b}PORTNAME@{ub}
argument. See @{"Options" Link "Options"} for more information.


	@{" Details            " Link "Details"}

	@{" General commands   " Link "General commands"}
	@{" History commands   " Link "History commands"}
	@{" Clipboard commands " Link "Clipboard commands"}
	@{" Requester commands " Link "Requester commands"}
	@{" Window commands    " Link "Window commands"}

@EndNode


@Node "Details" "ClipHistory.guide/Details"
@Toc "ARexx"

	@{u}@{b}Details@{uu}@{ub}

The @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands in @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} are documented in this manner:

	GetPrefs PREFS/A => VALUE/N

This line is then followed by an exaplanation of what the command does.
First on the line is the name of the command (in this example: @{b}GetPrefs@{ub}).
Case is not importand when looking for a command. After that follows the
arguments (in some cases, there are no arguments). The @{b}=>@{ub} arrow indicates
that what follows after it is the return value(s) (a command may return
several pieces of information). If no @{b}=>@{ub} arrow is present, then the
command returns no information.

The arguments use the standard @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} template. Thus, the keyword is
optional, but must be specified if the argument doesn't come in the
specified order. The keyword is the text before the @{b}/@{ub} char (and after any
@{b},@{ub} char), and the character after is a modifier, that tells you a
little about this argument. The following modifiers are used in this
document (there are others, but they are not used here):

@{b}/A@{ub}
	This argument is required. An error is returned if the argument
	isn't specified.

@{b}/N@{ub}
	This argument is numeric. It should be a valid decimal number, or
	an error is returned.

@{b}/S@{ub}
	This argument is a switch. The precense of this keyword enables a
	flag. If it is not present, the flag is not enabled.

@{b}/F@{ub}
	All text following the keyword is taken as the argument, without
	any modifications.

@{b}/M@{ub}
	Any number of arguments may be specified here.

These modifiers may be combined, so e.g. @{b}/A/N@{ub} means that a numeric value
must be specified. If no modifier is present, then there are no special
requirements upon the arguments (at least not anything the argument parser
(@{b}ReadArgs()@{ub}) can check).

These modifiers also applies to the return values. But first we need some
more information about the returns. The normal way of returning information
to an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script is to place it in @{i}RC @{ui}(limited to numeric
results, since this also returns errors from the command) or @{i}RESULT @{ui}(which
may contain anything). In @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} (and several other programs) there
is a little more control. Each command that returns some information also
have the two "hidden" (i.e. not documented) arguments; @{b}VAR@{ub} and @{b}STEM@{ub}. These
arguments specify were the return value should be placed.

The @{b}VAR@{ub} argument specifies in which variable the result should be placed.
This is baiscally the same as to return the value in @{i}RESULT.@{ui}

The @{b}STEM@{ub} argument is a little different, and is mostly useful for commands
that returns several pieces of information. The argument specifies the
"stem base name" for the return values. Thus, if a command have the return
template @{b}SIZE/N,ITEMS/N@{ub}, and we specified the stem base name @{b}TEST.@{ub}, then
the variables (stems) @{i}TEST.SIZE @{ui}and @{i}TEST.ITEMS @{ui}would hold the returns
(numeric values). If the return is in a normal variable, then the different
returns will be placed after each other, separated by spaces.

Now, there is a special return, which use the @{b}/M@{ub} modifier. If we use the
same stem base name as above, and the command have the return template
@{b}CLIP/M@{ub}, then the stem @{i}TEST.CLIP.COUNT @{ui}will hold the number of strings that
are returned, and @{i}TEST.CLIP.0, TEST.CLIP.1...@{ui} (until @{i}TEST.CLIP.x, @{ui} where @{b}x@{ub}
equals @{i}TEST.CLIP.COUNT @{ui}- 1) will hold the different strings. If the same
information is returned in a normal variable, then there will first be the
count, followed by the different strings, separated by spaces.

If an argument contains spaces, then it usually needs to be "double
quoted", like this:

	'"This is a correctly quoted string"'

This is needed since @{b}ARexx@{ub} first removes the single quotes (@{b}'@{ub}) when it
parses the string. @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} also needs quotes, to be able to separate
the arguments (these quotes must use the @{b}"@{ub} char).

Negative values also needs to be quoted (e.g. @{b}'-1'@{ub}). I'm not entirely sure
why this is needed. Strings (e.g. file names) that contain a @{b}:@{ub} char need
to be quoted as well.

If an error occured, the variable @{i}RC2 @{ui}will usually hold an error message
or a number (a dos error code. You can use @{b}Fault@{ub} to get an explanation for
a certain number). Note that "OPTIONS RESULTS" must have be used in the
script for this to happen.

All commands sets @{i}RC @{ui}to 10 for an error, 5 for a warning (e.g. asking for
a clip item that doesn't exist, or trying to do a window operation when the
window isn't open), and 0 for all ok. The error code 20 is reserved for
fatal errors, making @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} unable to parse the command, or properly
return the result. The typical reason for this to happen is lack of memory.
This is also returned if there are any pending commands when @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}
is about to exit.

The @{b}ARexx@{ub} interface in @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} was originally developed using
@{b}ARexxBox@{ub}. The generated code was then modified in several ways to get it
smaller (without loosing any functionality).

@EndNode


@Node "General commands" "ClipHistory.guide/General commands"
@Toc "ARexx"

	@{u}@{b}General commands@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}About@{ub}
	Simply open the about window. It will open on the same screen as
	the main window, or on the default public screen.

@{b}CxActivate@{ub}
	Activate the @{b}Commodities@{ub} interface. Similar to the "Active" gadget
	in the @{b}Exchange@{ub} program. Returns 5 if the interface
	already was active.

@{b}CxInactivate@{ub}
	Similar to @{b}CxActivate@{ub}, but inactivate the interface instead.
	Returns 5 if the interface already was inactive.

@{b}GetPrefs PREFS/A => VALUE/N@{ub}
	Get the state of the specified preferences item. Currently, the
	following items may be specified:

	@{b}ICONS@{ub}
		The "Create icons?" menu item (@{b}CREATEICONS@{ub} argument).

	@{b}REQTOOLS@{ub}
		The "ReqTools?" menu item (@{b}REQTOOLS@{ub} argument).

	@{b}TEXTASIFF@{ub}
		The "Text as IFF?" menu item (@{b}TEXTAIFF@{ub} argument).

	@{b}STICKY@{ub}
		The "Sticky?" menu item (@{b}STICKY@{ub} argument).

	This corresponds to what is shown in the @{"Options" Link "Menus"} menu. See the
	@{"Options" Link "Options"} section for more information about these options.

	Currently, the value is set to 1 if the flag is set, or 0 if the
	flag isn't set.

@{b}LockGUI@{ub}
	Lock the GUI, so that no input can be made (output can still me
	made). These calls nest, so remember to match them properly.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
	Quit @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}. No confirmation requester will be shown.

@{b}Show PUBSCREEN@{ub}
	Open the GUI. If a @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} argument is specified, then
	@{b}ClipHistory@{ub} will try to open on the specified public screen.

@{b}UnlockGUI@{ub}
	Decrease the nesting count for the GUI lock. If we reach zero,
	unlock the GUI, re-enabling user input.

	If you call this command too many times (making the count
	negative), the count is reset to zero, and return 10.

@{b}SetPrefs PREFS/A,VALUE/A/N@{ub}
	Set the state of the specified preferences item. Currently, the
	following items may be specified:

	@{b}ICONS@{ub}
		The "Create icons?" menu item (@{b}CREATEICONS@{ub} argument).

	@{b}REQTOOLS@{ub}
		The "ReqTools?" menu item (@{b}REQTOOLS@{ub} argument).

	@{b}TEXTASIFF@{ub}
		The "Text as IFF?" menu item (@{b}TEXTAIFF@{ub} argument).

	@{b}STICKY@{ub}
		The "Sticky?" menu item (@{b}STICKY@{ub} argument).

	This corresponds to what is shown in the @{"Options" Link "Menus"} menu. See the
	@{"Options" Link "Options"} section for more information about these options.

	If the value is 1 (or rather, not 0), then the flag is set, or if
	it is 0, the flag is cleared.

@EndNode


@Node "History commands" "ClipHistory.guide/History commands"
@Toc "ARexx"

	@{u}@{b}History commands@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}DeleteAllItems FORCE/S@{ub}
	Delete all items in the history. Use @{b}FORCE@{ub} to disable the
	confirmation requester. Returns 5 if the user cancelled the delete.

@{b}DeleteItem ITEM/N,FORCE/S@{ub}
	Delete the specified item, or the currently selected if none was
	specified.  Use @{b}FORCE@{ub} to disable the confirmation requester.
	Returns 5 if the user cancelled the requester, or the specified
	item didn't exist.

@{b}GetTextItem ITEM/N => CLIP/M@{ub}
	Return the contents of the specified item, of if not specified, the
	currently selected item. If the clip doesn't contain any text,
	return 5 in @{i}RC@{ui}. The @{b}CLIP@{ub} array will hold the different CHRS
	chunks. Usually, there is only one.

@{b}GetSelected => ITEM/N@{ub}
	Returns the ordinal number of the currently selected item, or -1 if
	no item is selected.

@{b}ItemInfo ITEM/N => TYPE,SIZE/N,NUMCHRS/N@{ub}
	Return some information about the specified item, or the currently
	selected item if no argument is given. The follwing information is
	returned:

	@{b}TYPE@{ub}
		The type of the IFF file, usually FTXT, ILBM or 8SVX.

	@{b}SIZE/N@{ub}
		The size of the clip, in bytes.

	@{b}NUMCHRS/N@{ub}
		The number of so called CHRS chunks in the clip. If 0, then
		the clip doesn't contain any text.

@{b}HistoryInfo => ITEMS/N,SIZE/N@{ub}
	Returns the following information about the history:

	@{b}ITEMS/N@{ub}
		Number of items currently in the history

	@{b}SIZE/N@{ub}
		The total size of the history, in bytes.

@{b}LockHistory@{ub}
	Lock the history, so that no items can be added to it. These calls
	nest, so remember to match them properly.

@{b}PutItem ITEM/N@{ub}
	Write the specified or currently selected item to the clipboard.

@{b}SaveItemAs NAME,ITEM/N,REQUEST/S@{ub}
	Save the specified or currently selected item to the specified
	file. If no file name is specified, or the @{b}REQUEST@{ub} flag is used,
	show a requester to let the user specify the name. @{b}NAME@{ub} then
	specifies the default name in the requester.

@{b}SelectItem ITEM/N,RELATIVE/S@{ub}
	Select the specified item. If the @{b}RELATIVE@{ub} flag is used, add the
	@{b}ITEM@{ub} to the currently selected item number (there must be a
	selected item for this to work).

@{b}ShowItem ITEM/N@{ub}
	Show the specified, or currently selected item. See @{b}SHOWCLIP@{ub} in
	the @{"Options" Link "Options"} chapter for more information about this.

@{b}UnlockHistory@{ub}
	Decrease the nesting count for the history lock. If we reach zero,
	unlock the history, making it possible to add new items.

	If you call this command too many times (making the count
	negative), the count is reset to zero, and return 10.

@EndNode


@Node "Clipboard commands" "ClipHistory.guide/Clipboard commands"
@Toc "ARexx"

	@{u}@{b}Clipboard commands@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}ClearClipboard@{ub}
	Clear the clipboard, by writing a special "empty" IFF-file to it.

@{b}GetTextClip => CLIP/M@{ub}
	Return the contents of the clipboard. If the clipboard doesn't
	contain any text, return 5 in @{i}RC@{ui}. The @{b}CLIP@{ub} array will hold the
	CHRS chunks. Usually, there will only be one.

@{b}PutFile NAME,REQUEST/S@{ub}
	Place the named file on the clipboard. If no name is given, or the
	@{b}REQUEST@{ub} flag is set, open a requester for the user to select a
	file. @{b}NAME@{ub} then specifies the default name in the requester.

	If the selected file is an IFF file, it will be copied as-is to the
	clipboard.  Otherwise, @{b}ClipHistory@{ub} assumes the file contains text,
	and will write it as an IFF FTXT file.

@{b}PutText TEXT/A/F@{ub}
	Put the specified text on the clipboard, as an IFF FTXT file.

@{b}SaveClipAs NAME,ITEM/N,REQUEST/S@{ub}
	Save the clipboard contents to the specified file. If no file name
	is specified, or the @{b}REQUEST@{ub} flag is used, show a requester to let
	the user specify the name. @{b}NAME@{ub} then specifies the default name in
	the requester.

@{b}ShowClip@{ub}
	Show the file in the clipboard. See the @{b}SHOWCLIP@{ub} argument in the
	@{"Options" Link "Options"} chapter for more information about this.

@EndNode


@Node "Requester commands" "ClipHistory.guide/Requester commands"
@Toc "ARexx"

	@{u}@{b}Requester commands@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}RequestFile TITLE,PATH,FILE,PATTERN => FILE@{ub}
	Show a file requester, with the specified title, default path and
	file, and the specified pattern, and return the selected name
	(@{b}FILE@{ub}). If the requester is cancelled, return 5 in @{i}RC@{ui}.

@{b}RequestNotify PROMPT/A@{ub}
	Show the specified prompt in a requester with a single "Ok" gadget.

@{b}RequestResponse TITLE,PROMPT/A,GADGETS@{ub}
	Show the specified prompt, with the specified title in a requester
	with an "Ok" and a "Cancel" gadget. Returns 0 if cancel was
	selected, or 5 if ok was selected.

	The @{b}GADGETS@{ub} option allows you to specify your own gadgets. The
	different gadgets should be separated by "|" chars. Returns 0 for
	the rightmost gadget, 1 for the leftmost, 2 for the next, and so
	on...

@EndNode


@Node "Window commands" "ClipHistory.guide/Window commands"
@Toc "ARexx"

	@{u}@{b}Window commands@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}ActivateWindow@{ub}
	Tries to activates the main window, if open. Returns 5 if the
	window isn't open.

@{b}ChangeWindow LEFTEDGE/N,TOPEDGE/N,WIDTH/N,HEIGHT/N@{ub}
	Move and resize the window to the given coordinates, or as close as
	possible. '-1' for a given coordinate means "don't change this one".
	Returns 5 if the window isn't open.

@{b}Hide@{ub}
	Simply close the window.

@{b}IsOpen => OPEN/N@{ub}
	Returns 1 if the window is open, or 0 if it isn't.

@{b}MoveWindow LEFTEDGE/N,TOPEDGE/N@{ub}
	Similar to @{b}ChangeWindow@{ub}, but this command only lets you change the
	position of the window.

@{b}SizeWindow WIDTH/N,HEIGHT/N@{ub}
	Similar to @{b}ChangeWindow@{ub}, but this command only lets you change the
	size of the window.

@{b}UnZoomWindow@{ub}
	If the window is zoomed, then unzoom it (possibly making it
	larger). Returns 5 if the window isn't open.

@{b}WindowToBack@{ub}
	Simply move the window behind any other window(s), if possible.
	Returns 5 if the window isn't open.

@{b}WindowToFront@{ub}
	Simply move the window in front of any other window(s), if possible.
	Returns 5 if the window isn't open.

@{b}ZoomWindow@{ub}
	If the window isn't zoomed, then zoom it (possibly making it
	smaller). Returns 5 if the window isn't open.

@EndNode


@Node "Future" "ClipHistory.guide/Future"

	@{u}@{b}The Future@{uu}@{ub}

There are a few things I might add to @{b}ClipHistory@{ub}:

	More IFF parsing. Now it is minimal, only reading/writing exactly
	what is on the clipboard, with a minor "support" for FTXT.
	Enhanced parsing could e.g. reduce the overhead for FTXT clips, by
	only saving the actual text.

	Load/save of the entire history. Perhaps automated, so that the
	history contents can be (automatically) restored after a reboot.

	Store large clips on disk rather than in memory.

	Show (scaled) versions of graphics clips somehow. This would
	require OS 3.0 for several reasons.

	Prefs window, to edit/save the settings. Perhaps as a separate
	prefs program. I have done some work in this direction, but I've
	never finished it...

	Some other way of "highlighting" non-text clips on OS 3.0 or
	better. The problem is that I don't know how I should change it. :)
	Please tell me if you have any idea.

	AppWindow support. Dropped icons should then be pasted to the
	clipboard.

	Split and join clips (at line feed chars)

These things are not that important for me, but feel free to send me a note
telling me what @{b}you@{ub} would like to see added (see @{"Author contact" Link "Author contact"}).

@EndNode


